# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chrysler-hemi-engine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The **Chrysler Hemi engine**, known by the trademark **Hemi** or **HEMI**, is a series of high-performance American overhead valve V8 engines built by Chrysler with hemispherical combustion chambers.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Three generations have been produced: the FirePower series (with displacements from 241 to 392 cu in (3.9 to 6.4 L) from 1951 until 1958; a 426 cu in (7.0 L) race and street engine from 1964 through 1971; and family of advanced Hemis (displacing between 5.7 and 6.4 L (348 and 391 cu in) since 2003.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Although Chrysler is most identified with "Hemi" as a marketing term, many other auto manufacturers have incorporated Hemispherical cylinder head designs.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] During the 1970s and 1980s, Chrysler also applied the term *Hemi* to their Australian-made Hemi-6 Engine, and a 4-cylinder Mitsubishi 2.6 L engine installed in various North American market vehicles.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The main advantage of a hemispherical head engine over other head designs is power.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] On the other hand, hemi head engines tend to have complex valve trains, are expensive to build, and are larger and heavier than conventional designs.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] A hemispherical combustion chamber is efficient, with an excellent surface-to-volume ratio, minimal heat loss to the cylinder head, and room for two large valves.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] However, it allows no more than two valves per cylinder because of their large size, and they are necessarily heavier than those in a multi-valve engine.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The intake and exhaust valves lie on opposite sides of the chamber and necessitate a "cross-flow" head design.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Because the combustion chamber is a partial hemisphere, a flat-topped piston would yield a low compression ratio unless a very long stroke is used.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The piston crown is domed to protrude into the head at top dead center to attain the desired compression ratio.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The result is a combustion chamber in the shape of the space between where the domed piston stops and the dome shape in the head receiving it.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The hemi-head design places the spark plug at or near the chamber's center to promote a strong flame front.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] However, if the hemi-head hemisphere is of equal diameter to the piston, there is minimal squish for proper turbulence to mix fuel and air thoroughly.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Thus, hemi-heads, because of their lack of squish, are more sensitive to fuel octane rating; a given compression ratio will require a higher octane rating to avoid detonation in a hemi engine than in some conventional engine designs, such as the wedge and bathtub.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The hemi head always has intake and exhaust valve stems that point in different directions, requiring a large, wide cylinder head and complex rocker arm geometry in both cam-in-block and single overhead cam engines (dual overhead cam engines may not have rocker arms).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] This adds to the overall width of the engine, limiting the vehicles in which it can be installed.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Significant challenges in the commercialization of engine designs using hemispherical chambers revolved around the valve actuation, specifically how to make it effective, efficient, and reliable at an acceptable cost.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] This complexity was referenced early in Chrysler's development of their 1950s hemi engine: the head was referred to in company advertising as the *Double Rocker Shaft* head.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Chrysler developed its first experimental hemi engine for the Republic P-47 Thunderbolt fighter aircraft.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The XIV-2220 was an inverted overhead-valve (OHV) V16 rated at 2,500 hp (1,860 kW).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The P-47 was already in production with a Pratt & Whitney radial engine when the XIV-2220 flew successfully in trials in 1945 as a possible upgrade, but the war was winding down and it did not go into production.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] However, the exercise gave Chrysler engineers valuable research and development experience with two-valve hemi combustion chamber dynamics and parameters.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] In addition to the aircraft engine, Chrysler and Continental Motors Company worked together to develop the air-cooled AV-1790-5B V12 Hemi engine used in the M47 Patton tank.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Chrysler applied their military experience with the hemispherical combustion chamber to its first automobile engine, an OHV V8 engine released under the name **FirePower**, not "Hemi," in 1950 for the 1951 model year.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The first version of the FirePower engine had a displacement of 331 cu in (5.4 L) and produced 180 bhp (134 kW).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Eventually, three of the four Chrysler divisions had their own version of the FirePower engine, with different displacements and designations, and having almost no parts in common.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] This lack of commonality was due in part to the three engine versions using different bore spacings (the center-to-center distance between adjacent cylinders).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Chrysler and Imperial called their versions the *FirePower*.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Dodge had a smaller version, known as the *Red Ram*.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Only Plymouth did not have a version, but retained the Dodge poly-head engines.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] There was no Plymouth Hemi engine until the 1964 426.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Briggs Cunningham used the Chrysler version in some of his race cars for international motorsports.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] A Chrysler-powered Cunningham C-5R won its class in 1953.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Cunningham switched away from these designs in 1959 when Chrysler temporarily abandoned the hemispherical concept in favor of the wedge-head B engine until 1964.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Carl Kiekhaefer also used the Chrysler engines in his NASCAR cars from 1955 and 1956, winning the Grand National Series championship both years.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Collectively, the 1951–1958 Hemi engines are now commonly retroactively referred to as first-generation Hemi engines, which can be identified by the rear-mounted distributor and the spark plugs in a row down the center of wide valve covers.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] There were plans in 1951 for a Plymouth dual overhead cam Hemi V6 displacing 235 cubic inches (3.9 L) designed by Chrysler's Powerplant Research and Engine Design division.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Known internally as **A173**, it was meant to be a powerful, fuel-efficient alternative to Ford's V8 and to replace Plymouth's venerable flathead six.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] However, the plans were scrapped because of high build costs and the then-unusual design.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] All Chrysler FirePower engines are oversquare; i.e. their bore is larger than their stroke.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] This first FirePower engine, used from 1951 to 1955, has a bore of 3.8125 in (96.8 mm) and a stroke of 3.625 in (92.1 mm) for a piston displacement of 331.1 cu in (5,425 cc), with a deck height of 10.385 in (263.8 mm) ("low deck").
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The bore spacing, shared by all Chrysler FirePower engines, was 4.5625 in (115.9 mm), the largest of any first generation Hemi engines.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Most used a two-barrel carburetor and produced 180 bhp (134 kW), with the exception of the 1955 Chrysler C-300 equipped with dual Carter WCFB four-barrel carburetors and was rated at 300 hp (224 kW).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The 300B engine was rated at 340 bhp (254 kW), while the New Yorker and Imperial 354 engine configuration produced 280 bhp (209 kW).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] For the 300B, an optional 355 hp (265 kW; 360 PS) version was available, making it the first American V8 to be rated at one horsepower per cubic inch.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] (Note that before 1972, horsepower was SAE gross (equivalent to maximum output); thereafter, it was rated as SAE net (power delivered to the transmission, less accessories, emission controls, exhaust system, and other power-sinks).) The 354 was also modified.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The Hemi was optimized for heavy-duty truck service.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] These were available with one or two four-barrel carburetors, and were offered in Dodge's heaviest-duty models as the 'Power Giant V-8' from 1957 through 1959; they were the largest of four Hemi truck engines offered by Dodge in the 1950s.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The 354 was also offered in certain models with polyspheric heads rather than hemi heads.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The combustion chambers on these had similarities to both hemi and wedge heads, but were closer in weight to wedge heads.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Thus, both 354 poly and 354 Hemi V8 engines were variously available in 1957.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The actual displacement is 392.67 cu in (6,435 cc).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The deck height, at 10.87 in (276.1 mm), was 1⁄2 in (13 mm) taller than that of the previous blocks.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Because its deck was taller, the heads were cast with wider intake ports so that earlier manifolds could be used with the new heads on the new taller block.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] For 1958, Chrysler offered the 392 in two configurations: 325 bhp (242 kW) with 9.25:1 compression and 345 bhp (257 kW) with 10:1 compression, both with a single four-barrel carburetor.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] A dual four-barrel version of the 392 available in the 1957–58 Chrysler 300C and 300D cars was rated at 375 bhp (280 kW); the 300D, and some marine and industrial engines, used a (now rare) adjustable rocker.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] An extremely rare option available on the 1958 300D was Bendix "Electrojector" fuel injection, with which the 392 was rated at 390 bhp (291 kW).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Due to reliability problems with the primitive onboard computer which controlled the injection system; however, 15 of the 16 300D cars built with the fuel injection option were recalled and retrofitted with carburetors.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] In the late 1950s and early 1960s, drag racers found the 392 to be a formidable engine and continued to run them competitively into the 1970s.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] DeSoto's Hemi engines were called FireDome and served as the naming convention for the DeSoto Firedome sedan.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] In 1952, DeSoto introduced its version of the FirePower (FireDome), with a bore of 3.625 in (92.08 mm) and stroke of 3.344 in (84.94 mm), for a displacement of 276.1 cu in (4.5 L).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The bore spacing, shared by all DeSoto FirePower engines, was 4.3125 in (109.54 mm).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] It was a hot seller, with 50,000 vehicles using the engine until it was replaced in 1954.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] In 1955, DeSoto increased the displacement of the FirePower (FireDome), by increasing the bore to 3.72 in (94.49 mm) for a displacement of 291 cu in (4.8 L).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Power output was 185 bhp (138 kW) with a 2-barrel carburetor for the Firedome models and 200 bhp (149 kW) with a 4-barrel carburetor for the Fireflite models.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] For 1956, the displacement for the Firedome and Fireflite models was increased again to 330 cu in (5.4 L) by increasing the stroke to 3.80 in (96.52 mm).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Power output was 230 bhp (172 kW) with a 2-barrel carburetor for the Firedome models and 255 bhp (190 kW) with a 4-barrel carburetor for the Fireflite models.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Displacement was increased again for the 1956 (DeSoto Adventurer only) and 1957 (Firedome and Fireflite models) to 341.1 cu in (5.6 L).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Bore was increased to 3.78 in (96.0 mm), but stroke remained at 3.80 in (96.5 mm).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The DeSoto Adventurer had a compression ratio of 9.5:1, using a special camshaft profile for hydraulic lifters, and produced 320 bhp (239 kW) using dual Carter WCFB four-barrel carburetors.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The 1956 Adventurer was the premiere named high-performance version—the DeSoto equivalent of the twin four-barrel Chrysler 300.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The largest DeSoto engine for 1957 was the DeSoto Adventurer offering 344.6 cu in (5.6 L) with square bore and stroke dimensions of 3.80 inches.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The DeSoto Adventurer used dual Carter WCFB four-barrel carburetors for a rating of 345 bhp (257 kW), producing one horsepower per cubic inch (the first American car to do so as standard equipment) using a similar intake manifold to the 1956 341 Adventurer and a similar camshaft.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The compression ratio remained at 9.5:1.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Dodge's Hemi was introduced in 1953 as the Red Ram.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Dodge did not have a V8 engine until one was developed specifically for the line in 1953 based on the 1951 Chrysler hemi design, but downsized for these smaller cars.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] They have the smallest bore center spacing of any hemi engine at 4.1875 in (106.4 mm).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] They do not share any major dimensions or components with the larger Chrysler and DeSoto hemi engines, or the Plymouth A engines.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] From 1955 to 1958 (see 1956 D500 Dodge D-500 cars and packages: early performance cars) lower-performance Hemi-based alternatives to the Dodge hemi were introduced by substituting less complex poly (single rocker shaft) heads and valve train parts, including one variant only built as a poly (259").
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] These were used in low-line 1955-58 DeSotos and Dodges, and 1955-56 high-line Plymouths.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Dodge introduced the 241.3 cu in (4.0 L) engine in 1953.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] With a low compression ratio of 7.0:1 (in 1953 and for the 1954 Meadowbrook), the 241 produced 140 bhp (104 kW).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] For 1954, the more senior Dodges received a higher 7.5:1 compression ratio 150 bhp (112 kW) version.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] This engine is not the same as the Plymouth 241, which had polyspheric heads.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The 241 Dodge Hemi only lasted two years, being replaced by the 270 for 1955.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The D553 1955/1956 Dodge Red Ram Hemi 270 displaced 270 cu in (4.4 L) and was used in premium 1955 and 1956 Dodge vehicles.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] It was not the same as the 270 poly-head.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] In the Dodge Coronet, the 270 produced 183 bhp (136 kW) at a compression ratio of 7.6:1.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] In higher trims like the Dodge Royal, the "Super Red Ram" featured a four-barrel carburetor and produced 193 bhp (144 kW) at the same compression ratio.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] For 1956, Dodge increased the displacement to 315 cu in (5.2 L) with a longer 3.80 in (96.5 mm) stroke and a taller raised-deck block, but used polyspheric rather than hemi heads on the base version.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The optional high-performance **D-500** version had a four-barrel carburetor and a larger-valved Dodge hemispherical combustion chambered head.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Also, a "race only" package called the D-500-1 or DASH 1 was available with a special aluminum dual four-barrel intake that sported a pair of Carter WCFB carburetors similar to the ones on the Chrysler 300B and DeSoto Adventurer.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] This engine used the same cylinder heads as the base D-500 model.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] In 1957 the D-501 was the Chrysler 354 engine, not a Dodge-based engine.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Dodge released the 325 cu in (5.3 L) "Super Red Ram" engine for 1957.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] It used a 3+11⁄16 in (93.7 mm; 3.69 in) bore and 3.80 in (96.5 mm) stroke, and a polyspheric chambered head (referenced as 'KDS') in its base version.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] A higher performance 325 was offered with hemi heads as the 'KD-500'.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The 'KD-500-1' came with dual four-barrel carburetors.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Even though the hemi headed offerings sported "dimples" in the valve covers for mechanical adjuster clearance, all engines had hydraulic lifters.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] “In December 1962 a request was made of engineering staff to develop an engine and vehicle combination capable of winning stock car competitive closed circuit track events throughout the country.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] It was further requested that a version of the engine suitable for use in supervised timed vehicle acceleration drag events also be made part of the engine portion of this program.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Both of these applications were to share the same basic design and development; thus a decision on the basic engine itself was one that required careful consideration.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] However, the decision for Chrysler was obvious.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The hemi engine had been a production engine from 1950 until it was discontinued in 1958.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The background of development that preceded the production version of the engine was available, as was experience in converting the engine for competition use.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Chrysler hemi engines had been used previously in track events, and were still in use in many drag events….The design of the new hemi engine began in January 1963 with the Feb.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] 23, 1964 Daytona Beach, Fla. race set as the first target date.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] A number of engine design avenues were initially explored in order to gain as many performance and durability features as possible while still retaining much of the existing [production] cylinder block tooling as practical.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The final design selected was deemed to have the potential necessary to win and the program was launched.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The engine requirements were to include a single 4 barrel carbuetor 426 cu in. track engine, and single barrel carburetor 396 cu in. track engine and a two 4 barrel carburetor 426 cu in. drag engine.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Immediately following the initial introduction of the engine, a production run of several hundred drag engines and cars were planned to be built.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The article continued: "Experimental procurement of the 426 cu in. hemi engine was started in July 1963 and was completed by the end of November.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The first engine ran under its own power on Dec.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] This engine was built as a track engine; the drag engine version was built later the same month.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The 396 cu in. track engine had subsequently been removed from the rules and the engine was never built.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] This 426 cu in. track engine was used extensively throughout the 1964 season.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The production of several hundred drag engines was completed by the end of the 1964 model year.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] A detuned high volume street version of the 426 hemi was designed, developed, released, and tooled as part of the 1966 model offering…With this release, full eligibility of the engine for 1966 track use was again established.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The 1960s 426 was the first engine called "Hemi" by Chrysler, the 426 was nicknamed the "elephant engine" at the time, a reference to its high power, heavy weight, and large physical dimensions.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Its 10.72 in (272.3 mm) deck height and 4.80 in (121.9 mm) bore spacing made it the biggest engine in racing at the time.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The 426 Hemi "Track" version, produced for use in NASCAR, was raced in a Plymouth Belvedere in 1964 by drivers such as Richard Petty.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] It was not initially available to the general public.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Complaints by Ford regarding its power led to the "Race Hemi" being banned from NASCAR's 1965 season due to its unavailability in production vehicles.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] However, several special homologated production versions of the Dodge Dart, the Plymouth Fury, and later, in 1965, the Dodge Coronet, were produced with aluminum fenders and bumpers for drag racing and made available to the general public.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Chrysler introduced the "Street Hemi" in 1966 for its intermediate range of cars and sold the required number of Hemi engines to the public to homologate its use for stock car racing in NASCAR events in 1966.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The “Street” engine featured a heated intake manifold, cast iron exhaust manifolds, automatic choke, and a milder cam.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The "Street Hemi" version was rated at 425 bhp (431 PS; 317 kW) at 5000 rpm SAE gross and 490 lb⋅ft (664 N⋅m) at 4000 rpm of torque.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] In actual dynamometer testing, it produced 433.5 hp (323 kW; 440 PS) and 472 lb⋅ft (640 N⋅m) of torque in purely stock form.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Chrysler's sales literature published both the gross 425 hp (317 kW; 431 PS) and net 350 hp (261 kW; 355 PS) ratings for 1971.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The “Track” and “Drag” engines were more alike than the “Street” engine was with either.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Among differening specifications in these racing engines for 1964-66 were: piston weights, intake valve diameter, water pumps, carburetion, camshaft profiles, and construction material (more aluminum and magnesium in “Drag” engine).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] There were many differences between the Hemi and the 426 Wedge, including the Hemi having cross-bolted steel main bearing caps and a different head bolt pattern.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Although all manufacturers were familiar with multi-valve engines and hemispherical combustion chambers, adding more valves per cylinder and designing the complex valvetrain they require were expensive ways of improving the high–revolutions per minute (rpm) breathing of production vehicles.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] By canting the angle of the NASCAR-mandated two valves per cylinder, significantly larger valves could be used.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Both the Chrysler 426 Hemi and all Chrysler RB engines were oversquare, with the 426 Hemi and 426 Wedge sharing a 4+1⁄4 in × 3+3⁄4 in (108.0 mm × 95.3 mm) bore and stroke.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Blocks for the 426 Hemi were stress relieved at the factory, to prevent cracking under high RPM loads.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] It was a family of engines covering everything from street engines to light weight competition engines.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] While the basic design was a hemispherical head with a center spark plug, the parameters varied greatly, depending on the intended use of the engine.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Differences between the racing Hemis and the street version, including but not limited to compression ratio, camshaft, intake manifold, exhaust manifold.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Some 1960s NASCAR and NHRA Hemi engines featured magnesium cross-ram intake manifolds and magnesium oil pans in an attempt to reduce the massive weight of the overall engine, along with chain-driven internal dry sump oil systems.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The main differences were in airflow and endurance to repeated high stress testing.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The Street Hemis were designed to be long lasting with high idle capabilities, while the A-864 and A-990 heads, designed for use on the race track, were designed for maximum volumetric efficiency at high engine speeds.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Almost every modern street and racing engine that is known as a Hemi has switched to using an aluminum engine block.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Using the high grade 356-T6 aluminum aftermarket blocks and heads have improved the cooling of the engine significantly, and has reduced the weight of the iron components by over 100lbs.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Modern engine design using these new material components is utilizing forged aluminum pistons to deal with the additional heat of the higher RPM’s and load.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The current-production "HEMI" engine heads are flatter and more complex than the 1950s–'70s Hemi V8 chamber.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The combustion chambers are no longer truly hemispherical.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] It uses a coil-on-plug (distributor-less) ignition system and two spark plugs per cylinder to shorten flame travel leading to more consistent combustion and reduced emissions.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Like most of Chrysler's past-model Hemi-head engines, the 5.7 L version is rated at approximately one horsepower per cubic inch (the current engines are SAE net, whereas the old Hemi engines were rated SAE gross).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] It also achieved 4% better fuel economy.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Variable valve timing (VVT) was also introduced.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] A new variable displacement technology called Multi-Displacement System (MDS) is used in some versions which can shut off two cylinders on each bank under light load to improve fuel economy.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The 5.7 L HEMI was released for model year 2003 on the Dodge Ram pickup trucks to supplant the Magnum 5.9 engine.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] From 2004 to 2013, it was the only available gasoline engine in the Ram Heavy Duty.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Chrysler later made the 5.7 L Hemi available in all models of the 2004 Dodge Ram, Dodge Durango, the 2005 Chrysler 300C, Dodge Magnum R/T, Jeep Grand Cherokee, the 2006 Dodge Charger R/T, Jeep Commander, the 2007 Chrysler Aspen, the 2009 Dodge Challenger R/T, and the 2022 Jeep Wagoneer.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] For manual transmission applications (Challenger and 3/4- and 1-ton Ram pickups), cylinder deactivation is not included.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The 5.7 L (345 cu in) Hemi in the Ram delivered 345 hp (257 kW) and 375 lb⋅ft (508 N⋅m), but 340 hp (254 kW) and 390 lb⋅ft (529 N⋅m) for the 300C and Magnum R/T, which is exactly 100 hp (75 kW) more than the old 5.9 engine.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] It is a 90-degree V8, 2-valve pushrod design like the past Magnum series engines, displacing 5,654 cc (345 cu in), with a bore of 3.917 in (99.49 mm) and a stroke of 3.578 in (90.88 mm).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The 5.7 L Hemi is made at Chrysler's Saltillo Engine plant in Ramos Arizpe, Mexico.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The Hemi was on the Ward's 10 Best Engines list for 2003 through 2007, and again in 2009.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Chrysler made various revisions to the 5.7 L for the 2009 model year.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The first for all applications was what Chrysler called Variable Camshaft Timing or VCT.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] VCT (which is essentially variable valve timing) uses an oil control valve that controls oil flow to a unique camshaft sprocket that contains a phasing device, which depending on the operation of the oil control valve, either advances or retards camshaft timing.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Cylinder heads were revised to increase flow.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Though the intake manifold was also changed on all applications, it was still model-specific.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The Dodge Ram, non-Hybrid Electric Vehicle (HEV) Chrysler Aspens, and non-HEV Dodge Durango utilized an active intake manifold with a short runner valve to optimize torque and horsepower.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] At lower engine speeds, the valve was closed, resulting in improved low-end torque from the longer runners.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] At higher engine speeds, the valve was opened, diverting the incoming air into the center of the manifold.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The shorter runners resulted in improved horsepower.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Passenger cars, Jeep vehicles, as well as HEV Chrysler Aspen and HEV Dodge Durango did not use this manifold; instead, these vehicles utilized a passive intake manifold, which did not have a short runner valve.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Also, the new cylinder head came with different spark plug seats: tapered seats were replaced with gasket seats.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] This change made it impossible to use the old OE Champion RE14MCC4, so the new spark plugs that came with 5.7 HEMI became NGK LZFR5C-11.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Besides different seats, the spark plug gap grew from .039" (1.0 mm) to .043" (1.1 mm).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Engines mated to the six-speed manual transmission or used in the Ram Heavy Duty did not feature the Multi-Displacement System (MDS).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The Hemi was also available in a 6,059 cc (6.1 L; 369.7 cu in) version that was developed in 2004 for the 2005 model year Chrysler 300C SRT8.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The engine's bore × stroke was 103 mm × 90.9 mm (4.055 in × 3.579 in), and many other changes were made to allow it to produce 425 bhp (317 kW; 431 PS) at 6,200 rpm and 420 lb⋅ft (569 N⋅m) of torque at 4,800 rpm.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The engine block differed from the 5.7, with revised coolant channels and oil jets to cool the pistons.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] A forged crankshaft, lighter pistons, and strengthened connecting rods improved durability.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] A cast aluminium intake manifold was tuned for high-rpm power and did not include variable-length technology.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Chrysler's Multi-Displacement System was not used on the 6.1.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] For 2015, Chrysler introduced an all-new high performance supercharged variant of the Hemi engine, called the **Hellcat** (named after the Grumman F6F Hellcat).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] It features the same 4.09 in (103.9 mm) bore as the 6.4 L Hemi and the same 3.578 in (90.9 mm) stroke as the 5.7 L, giving it a total displacement of 6,166 cc (6.2 L; 376.3 cu in).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The supercharger is a 2,380 cc (145 cu in) twin-screw IHI unit with integrated charge coolers, capable of producing 11.6 psi (80 kPa; 0.80 bar) of boost.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] This engine is rated at 707 hp (717 PS; 527 kW) at 6,000 rpm and 650 lb⋅ft (881 N⋅m) at 4,000 rpm of torque and has a compression ratio of 9.5:1.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] This engine was the most powerful engine produced by Chrysler as well as the most powerful production engine ever in a muscle car until the Dodge Demon was introduced.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] This engine is not equipped with Chrysler's Multi-Displacement System.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] In 2017, Mopar announced that it would sell it as a crate engine under the name Hellcrate.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] A Redeye version with 797 hp (808 PS; 594 kW) debuted in the Dodge Challenger in 2019, followed by the Dodge Charger in 2021.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The 2026 and onward version of the engine found in the TRX and Rumble Bee versions of the Ram 1500 use newer equipment and produce 777 hp (788 PS; 579 kW) and 680 lb⋅ft (922 N⋅m).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The Demon version of the Hemi V8 features a number of improvements over the Hellcat variant.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] It is fitted with a larger, 2.7 L twin-screw supercharger, as well as reinforced reciprocating components, a new camshaft, and several other valvetrain upgrades.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] With these improvements, the Challenger SRT Demon is rated at 808 hp (603 kW) on 91-octane pump gasoline, and 840 horsepower when running on 100-octane unleaded racing gasoline.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Cooling is aided by a functional Air-Grabber hood scoop, as well as a unique charge cooling system that makes use of the air-conditioning coolant to lower the intake charge air temperature.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Chrysler displayed a larger and more powerful 392-cubic-inch (6.4 L) HEMI in 2005 with a factory-rated output of 525 hp (391 kW; 532 PS) and 510 lb⋅ft (691 N⋅m) torque.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] It is equipped with high-strength forged aluminum alloy pistons.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] This engine has been available since 2007, as a crate engine under the name 392 HEMI.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The production version of the 392 HEMI was developed in 2010, launched in the 2011 model year Dodge Challenger SRT8 with variable camshaft timing as well as MDS in cars with automatic transmissions.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The new 392 HEMI, codenamed "Apache," is based on the third-generation 5.7 L HEMI, codenamed "Eagle," and shares few parts with the 392 crate engine.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The "Apache" 6.4L features forged steel crankshaft, hypereutectic cast aluminum pistons with floating pins, 10.9:1 compression ratio, 2.14in intake valves and 1.65in exhaust valves.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Special-edition Chargers and Challengers equipped with this engine, and the engines themselves, featured "392 HEMI" badging in commemorative reference to the first-generation engine of the same displacement.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] For the 2015 model year, horsepower was increased to 485 hp (362 kW) and torque to 475 lb⋅ft (644 N⋅m) in the Charger and Challenger *SRT 392* (2015–2018) and *R/T Scat Pack* (2015–2023) models; the Grand Cherokee SRT only saw a 5 bhp increase.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Export models of the Chrysler 300 SRT retained the 470 hp (350 kW) and 470 lb⋅ft (637 N⋅m) output.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Starting in model year 2014, the Ram 2500 and 3500 trucks, and Ram 3500, 4500, and 5500 chassis-cabs offered a revised version of the 6.4 L known as the "BGE", Big Gas Engine.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Compared to the 6.4L in passenger cars/SUVs, the truck version is tuned for durability and a power band more suitable for hauling and towing, and compatibility with lower octane fuel.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The BGE 6.4L features a grey cast iron block shared with the 6.2L Hellcat engine, which features reinforced bulkheads and ribs.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The aluminum heads of the BGE 6.4L are also shared with the Hellcat 6.2, manufactured with additional ribs and cast from 356-T6 aluminum.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The BGE 6.4L features dished pistons to achieve a lower compression ratio of 10.0:1, vs the 10.9:1 compression ratio of the SRT variant.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The engine rpm is limited to 5800 rpm in pickup truck models, and 4660 rpm when paired to the Aisin transmission.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] In 2016, it replaced the 5.7 L as the standard gasoline engine in the chassis-cab models, and for 2019 became the standard gasoline engine in 2500 and 3500 models.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] At the 2012 North American International Auto Show in Detroit, Dodge debuted a Mopar Customized Dodge Charger "Redline" that featured a modern 426-cubic-inch (7.0 L) HEMI V8 engine rated at 590 hp (440 kW; 598 PS).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The Hellephant name is a spin on the nickname of the original 426-cubic-inch (7.0 L) HEMI, Elephant, and the modern Supercharged 6.2-liter Hellcat HEMIs.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] It is a crate engine, supercharged as standard, producing 1,000 hp (746 kW) and 950 lb⋅ft (1,288 N⋅m) of torque.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] From February to April 2005, DaimlerChrysler hosted a "What Can You HEMI?" contest promoting alternative uses of the HEMI engines.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The top five finalists include HEMI Snowblower, HEMI-Go-Round carousel, "HEMI on Ice" ice resurfacer, HEMI-Shredder, and HEMI Big Wheel (i.e., the child's tricycle of the 1970s).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] The winner was the HEMI Big Wheel, which had a 5.7 L Hemi in the back that was installed backwards; thus, reverse became the only forward gear.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/426-hemi] Plate steel was the predominant material, while a rolled tube of steel had to be utilized for the front tire because there were no such tires 4-foot (122 cm) in diameter that were as narrow as needed for this project.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Chemically, aluminium is a post-transition metal in the boron group; as is common for the group, aluminium forms compounds primarily in the +3 oxidation state.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The aluminium cation Al3+ is small and highly charged; as such, it has more polarizing power, and bonds formed by aluminium have a more covalent character.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The strong affinity of aluminium for oxygen leads to the common occurrence of its oxides in nature.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is found on Earth primarily in rocks in the crust, where it is the third-most abundant element after oxygen and silicon, rather than in the mantle, and virtually never as the free metal.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] It is obtained industrially by mining bauxite, a sedimentary rock rich in aluminium minerals.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The discovery of aluminium was announced in 1825 by Danish physicist Hans Christian Ørsted.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The first industrial production of aluminium was initiated by French chemist Henri Étienne Sainte-Claire Deville in 1856.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium became much more available to the public with the Hall–Héroult process developed independently by French engineer Paul Héroult and American engineer Charles Martin Hall in 1886, and the mass production of aluminium led to its extensive use in industry and everyday life.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] In 1954, aluminium became the most produced non-ferrous metal, surpassing copper.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] In the 21st century, most aluminium was consumed in transportation, engineering, construction, and packaging in the United States, Western Europe, and Japan.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The standard atomic weight of aluminium is low in comparison with many other metals, giving it the low density responsible for many of its uses.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Despite its prevalence in the environment, no living thing is known to metabolize aluminium salts, but aluminium is well tolerated by plants and animals.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Because of the abundance of these salts, the potential for a biological role for them is of interest, and studies are ongoing.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium metal has an appearance ranging from silvery white to dull gray depending on its surface roughness.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium mirrors provides high reflectivity for light in the ultraviolet, visible (on par with silver), and far infrared regions.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is also good at reflecting solar radiation, although prolonged exposure to sunlight in air can deteriorate the reflectivity of the metal; this may be prevented if aluminium is anodized, which adds a protective layer of oxide on the surface.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The density of aluminium is 2.70 g/cm3, about one-third that of steel, much lower than other commonly encountered metals, making aluminium parts easily identifiable through their lightness.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium's low density compared to most other metals arises from the fact that its unit cell size is relatively large in proportion to the number of nucleons.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The only lighter metals are the metals of groups 1 and 2, which, apart from beryllium and magnesium, are too reactive for structural use (and beryllium is very toxic).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is not as strong or stiff as steel, but the low density makes up for this in the aerospace industry and for many other applications where light weight and relatively high strength are crucial.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Pure aluminium is quite soft and lacking in strength.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] In most applications, various aluminium alloys are used instead because of their higher strength and hardness.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The yield strength of pure aluminium is 7–11 MPa, while aluminium alloys have yield strengths ranging from 200 MPa to 600 MPa.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is ductile, with a percent elongation of 50–70%, and malleable allowing it to be easily drawn and extruded; it is also easily machined and cast.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is an excellent thermal and electrical conductor, and the amount of aluminium required to match the same amperage in copper weighs only half as much.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is capable of superconductivity, with a superconducting critical temperature of 1.2 kelvin and a critical magnetic field of about 100 gauss (10 milliteslas).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] It is paramagnetic and thus essentially unaffected by static magnetic fields.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] However, the high electrical conductivity means that it is strongly affected by alternating magnetic fields through the induction of eddy currents.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] An aluminium atom has 13 electrons with an electron configuration of [Ne] 3s2 3p1, with three electrons beyond a stable noble gas configuration.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Accordingly, the combined first three ionization energies of aluminium are far lower than the fourth ionization energy alone.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Such an electron configuration is shared with the other well-characterized members of its group, boron, gallium, indium, and thallium; it is also expected for nihonium.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium can surrender its three outermost electrons in many chemical reactions (see below).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The electronegativity of aluminium is 1.61 on the Pauling scale.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] A free aluminium atom has an atomic radius of 143 pm.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] With the three outermost electrons removed, the radius shrinks to 39 pm for a 4-coordinated atom or 53.5 pm for a 6-coordinated atom.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] At standard temperature and pressure, aluminium atoms (when not affected by atoms of other elements) form a face-centered cubic crystal system bound by metallic bonding provided by atoms' outermost electrons; hence, aluminium (at these conditions) is a metal.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] This crystal system is shared by many other metals, such as lead and copper; the size of a unit cell of aluminium is comparable to that of those other metals.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] This system, however, is not shared by the other members of its group: boron has ionization energies too high to allow metallization, thallium has a hexagonal close-packed structure, and gallium and indium have unusual structures that are not close-packed like those of aluminium and thallium.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The few electrons that are available for metallic bonding in aluminium are a probable cause for it being soft with a low melting point and low electrical resistivity.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium has one stable isotope, 27Al, which comprises virtually all of the naturally-occurring element.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] This is common for elements with an odd atomic number.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] It is therefore a mononuclidic element for standard atomic weight, which is determined completely by that isotope.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is useful in nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR), as its single stable isotope (though quadrupolar) has a high NMR sensitivity.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] All other isotopes of aluminium are radioactive.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The most stable of these is 26Al, with a half-life of 717,000 years.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] While it was present along with stable 27Al in the interstellar medium from which the Solar System formed (believed to have been produced by stellar nucleosynthesis also), no detectable amount could have survived the time since the formation of the planet.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] However, minute traces of 26Al are still produced from decay of argon in the atmosphere induced by ionizing radiation of cosmic rays.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The ratio of 26Al to 10Be has been used for the radiodating of geological processes over 105 to 106 year time scales, in particular transport, deposition, sediment storage, burial times, and erosion.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Most meteorite scientists believe that the energy released by the decay of 26Al was responsible for the melting and differentiation of some asteroids after their formation 4.55 billion years ago.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The other known isotopes of aluminium, with mass numbers ranging from 20 to 43, all have half-lives less than 7 minutes, as do the four detected metastable states.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium combines characteristics of pre- and post-transition metals.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Since it has few available electrons for metallic bonding, like the heavier group 13 elements, it has the characteristic physical properties of a post-transition metal, with longer-than-expected interatomic distances.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Furthermore, as Al3+ is a small and highly charged cation, it is strongly polarizing, and bonding in aluminium compounds tends towards covalency; this behavior is similar to that of beryllium (Be2+), displaying an example of a diagonal relationship.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The underlying core of electrons under aluminium's valence shell is that of the preceding noble gas, whereas those of the heavier group 13 elements gallium, indium, thallium, and nihonium also include a filled d-subshell and in some cases a filled f-subshell.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Hence, the inner electrons of aluminium shield the valence electrons almost completely, unlike those of the heavier group 13 elements.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] As such, aluminium is the most electropositive metal in its group, and its hydroxide is in fact more basic than that of gallium.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium also bears minor similarities to boron (a metalloid), which is in the same group: AlX3 compounds are valence isoelectronic to BX3 compounds (they have the same valence electronic structure), and both behave as Lewis acids and readily form adducts.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Additionally, one of the main motifs of boron chemistry is regular icosahedral structures, and aluminium forms an important part of many icosahedral quasicrystal alloys, including the Al–Zn–Mg class.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium has a high chemical affinity to oxygen, which renders it suitable for use as a reducing agent in the thermite reaction.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] A fine powder of aluminium reacts explosively on contact with liquid oxygen; under normal conditions, however, aluminium forms a thin oxide layer (~5 nm at room temperature) that protects the metal from further corrosion by oxygen, water, or dilute acid, a process termed passivation.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is not attacked by oxidizing acids because of its passivation.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] This allows aluminium to be used to store reagents such as nitric acid, concentrated sulfuric acid, and some organic acids.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] In hot, concentrated hydrochloric acid, aluminium reacts with water through evolution of hydrogen, and it reacts in aqueous sodium or potassium hydroxide at room temperature to form aluminates; protective passivation under these conditions is negligible.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is also corroded by dissolved chlorides, such as common sodium chloride.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The oxide layer on aluminium is also destroyed by contact with mercury due to amalgamation or by contact with salts of some electropositive metals.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] As such, the strongest aluminium alloys are less corrosion-resistant due to galvanic reactions with alloyed copper, and aluminium's corrosion resistance is greatly reduced by aqueous salts, particularly in the presence of dissimilar metals.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium reacts with most nonmetals upon heating, forming compounds such as aluminium nitride (AlN), aluminium sulfide (Al2S3), and the aluminium halides (AlX3).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] It also forms a wide range of intermetallic compounds involving metals from every group on the periodic table.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The vast majority of aluminium compounds, including all aluminium-containing minerals and all commercially significant aluminium compounds, feature aluminium in the oxidation state 3+.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The coordination number of such compounds varies, but generally Al3+ is either six- or four-coordinate.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Almost all compounds of aluminium(III) are colorless.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] In aqueous solution, Al3+ exists as the hexa-aqua cation [Al(H2O)6]3+, which has an approximate Ka of 10−5.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Such solutions are acidic because this cation can act as a proton donor and progressively hydrolyze until a precipitate of aluminium hydroxide, Al(OH)3, forms.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] This is useful for clarification of water, since the precipitate nucleates on suspended particles in the water, hence removing them.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Increasing the pH even further leads to the hydroxide dissolving again as aluminate, [Al(H2O)2(OH)4]−, is formed.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium hydroxide forms both salts and aluminates and dissolves in acid and alkali, as well as on fusion with acidic and basic oxides.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] This behavior of Al(OH)3 is termed amphoterism and is characteristic of weakly basic cations that form insoluble hydroxides and whose hydrated species can also donate their protons.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] One effect of this is that aluminium salts with weak acids are hydrolyzed in water to the aquated hydroxide and the corresponding nonmetal hydride: for example, aluminium sulfide yields hydrogen sulfide.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] However, some salts like aluminium carbonate exist in aqueous solution but are unstable as such.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Only incomplete hydrolysis takes place for salts with strong acids, such as the halides, nitrate, and sulfate.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] For similar reasons, anhydrous aluminium salts cannot be made by heating their "hydrates": hydrated aluminium chloride is in fact not AlCl3·6H2O but [Al(H2O)6]Cl3, and the Al–O bonds are so strong that heating is not sufficient to break them and form Al–Cl bonds.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Unlike the structures of the three heavier trihalides, aluminium fluoride (AlF3) features six-coordinate aluminium, which explains its involatility and insolubility as well as high heat of formation.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Each aluminium atom is surrounded by six fluorine atoms in a distorted octahedral arrangement, with each fluorine atom being shared between the corners of two octahedra.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Such {AlF6} units also exist in complex fluorides such as cryolite, Na3AlF6.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] AlF3 melts at 1,290 °C (2,354 °F) and is made by reaction of aluminium oxide with hydrogen fluoride gas at 700 °C (1,300 °F).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] With heavier halides, the coordination numbers are lower.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The other trihalides are dimeric or polymeric with tetrahedral four-coordinate aluminium centers.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium trichloride (AlCl3) has a layered polymeric structure below its melting point of 192.4 °C (378 °F) but transforms on melting to Al2Cl6 dimers.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] At higher temperatures those increasingly dissociate into trigonal planar AlCl3 monomers similar to the structure of BCl3.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium tribromide and aluminium triiodide form Al2X6 dimers in all three phases and hence do not show such significant changes of properties upon phase change.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] These materials are prepared by treating aluminium with the halogen.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The aluminium trihalides form many addition compounds or complexes.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Their Lewis acidic nature makes them useful as catalysts for the Friedel–Crafts reactions.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium trichloride has major industrial uses involving this reaction, such as in the manufacture of anthraquinones and styrene.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium trichloride is also often used as the precursor for many other aluminium compounds and as a reagent for converting nonmetal fluorides into the corresponding chlorides (a transhalogenation reaction).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium forms one stable oxide with the chemical formula Al2O3, commonly called alumina.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] It can be found in nature in the mineral corundum, the α-alumina phase.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Its crystalline form, corundum, is very hard (Mohs hardness 9), has a high melting point of 2,045 °C (3,713 °F), has very low volatility, is chemically inert, and is a good electrical insulator.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] It is often used in abrasives (such as sandpaper) as a refractory material and in ceramics.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] It is also the starting material for the electrolytic production of aluminium.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Sapphire and ruby are impure corundum contaminated with trace amounts of other metals.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The two main oxide-hydroxides, AlO(OH), are boehmite and diaspore.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] There are three main trihydroxides: bayerite, gibbsite, and nordstrandite, which differ in their crystalline structure (polymorphs).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Many other intermediate and related structures are also known.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Most of these Al-O-OH systems are produced from ores by a variety of wet processes using acid and bases.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Heating the hydroxides leads to the formation of corundum.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] These materials are of central importance to the production of aluminium and are themselves extremely useful.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Some mixed oxide phases are also very useful, such as spinel (MgAl2O4), Na-β-alumina (NaAl11O17), and tricalcium aluminate (Ca3Al2O6), an important mineral phase in Portland cement.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The only stable chalcogenides under normal conditions are aluminium sulfide (Al2S3), selenide (Al2Se3), and telluride (Al2Te3).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] All three are prepared by direct reaction of their elements at about 1,000 °C (1,800 °F) and quickly hydrolyze completely in water to yield aluminium hydroxide and the respective hydrogen chalcogenide.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] As aluminium is a small atom relative to these chalcogens, these have four-coordinate tetrahedral aluminium with various polymorphs having structures related to wurtzite, with two-thirds of the possible metal sites occupied either in an orderly (α) or random (β) fashion.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The sulfide also has a γ form related to γ-alumina and an unusual high-temperature hexagonal form where half the aluminium atoms have tetrahedral four-coordination and the other half have trigonal bipyramidal five-coordination.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Four pnictides – aluminium nitride (AlN), aluminium phosphide (AlP), aluminium arsenide (AlAs), and aluminium antimonide (AlSb) – are known.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] They are all III-V semiconductors isoelectronic to silicon and germanium, all of which but AlN have the zinc blende structure.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] All four can be made by high-temperature (and possibly high-pressure) direct reaction of their component elements.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium alloys well with most other metals (with the exception of most alkali metals and group 13 metals) and over 150 intermetallics with other metals are known.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Preparation involves heating fixed metals together in certain proportions, followed by gradual cooling and annealing.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Bonding in them is predominantly metallic and the crystal structure primarily depends on efficiency of packing.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] There are few compounds with lower oxidation states.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Some are aluminium(I) compounds: AlF, AlCl, AlBr, and AlI all exist in the gaseous phase when the respective trihalide is heated with aluminium, and at cryogenic temperatures.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] A stable derivative of aluminium monoiodide is the cyclic adduct formed with triethylamine, Al4I4(NEt3)4.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Al2O and Al2S also exist but are very unstable.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Very simple aluminium(II) compounds are invoked or observed in the reactions of Al metal with oxidants.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] For example, aluminium monoxide, AlO, has been detected in the gas phase after explosion and in stellar absorption spectra.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] More thoroughly investigated are compounds of the formula R4Al2 which contain an Al–Al bond and where R is a large organic ligand.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] A variety of compounds of empirical formula AlR3 and AlR1.5Cl1.5 exist.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The aluminium trialkyls and triaryls are either reactive, volatile, and colorless liquids or low-melting solids.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] They catch fire spontaneously in air and react with water, thus necessitating precautions when handling them.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] They often form dimers, unlike their boron analogues, but this tendency diminishes for branched-chain alkyls (e.g.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] For example, triisobutylaluminium exists as an equilibrium mixture of the monomer and dimer.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] These dimers, such as trimethylaluminium (Al2Me6), usually feature tetrahedral Al centers formed by dimerization with some alkyl group bridging between both aluminium atoms.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] They are hard acids and react readily with ligands, forming adducts.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] In industry, they are mostly used in alkene insertion reactions, as discovered by Karl Ziegler, most importantly in "growth reactions" that form long-chain unbranched primary alkenes and alcohols, and in the low-pressure polymerization of ethene and propene.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] There are also some heterocyclic and cluster organoaluminium compounds involving Al–N bonds.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The industrially most important aluminium hydride is lithium aluminium hydride (LiAlH4), which is used as a reducing agent in organic chemistry.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] It can be produced from lithium hydride and aluminium trichloride.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The simplest hydride, aluminium hydride or alane, is not as important.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] It is a polymer with the formula (AlH3)*n*, which is in contrast to the corresponding boron hydride that is a dimer with the formula (BH3)2.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium's per-particle abundance in the Solar System is 3.15 ppm (parts per million).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] It is the twelfth most abundant of all elements and third most abundant among the elements that have odd atomic numbers, after hydrogen and nitrogen.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The only stable isotope of aluminium, 27Al, is the eighteenth most abundant nucleus in the universe.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] It is created almost entirely after fusion of carbon in massive stars that will later become Type II supernovas: this fusion creates 26Mg, which upon capturing free protons and neutrons, becomes aluminium.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Some smaller quantities of 27Al are created in hydrogen burning shells of evolved stars, where 26Mg can capture free protons.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Essentially all aluminium now in existence is 27Al.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] 26Al was present in the early Solar System with abundance of 0.005% relative to 27Al but its half-life of 728,000 years is too short for any original nuclei to survive; 26Al is therefore extinct.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Unlike for 27Al, hydrogen burning is the primary source of 26Al, with the nuclide emerging after a nucleus of 25Mg catches a free proton.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] However, the trace quantities of 26Al that do exist are the most common gamma ray emitter in the interstellar gas; if the original 26Al were still present, gamma ray maps of the Milky Way would be brighter.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Overall, the Earth is about 1.59% aluminium by mass (seventh in abundance by mass).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium occurs in greater proportion in the Earth's crust than in the universe at large.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] This is because aluminium easily forms the oxide and becomes bound into rocks and stays in the Earth's crust, while less reactive metals sink to the core.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] In the Earth's crust, aluminium is the most abundant metallic element (8.23% by mass) and the third most abundant of all elements (after oxygen and silicon).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] A large number of silicates in the Earth's crust contain aluminium.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] In contrast, the Earth's mantle is only 2.38% aluminium by mass.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium also occurs in seawater at a concentration of 0.41 μg/kg.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Because of its strong affinity for oxygen, aluminium is almost never found in the elemental state; instead it is found in oxides or silicates.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Feldspars, the most common group of minerals in the Earth's crust, are aluminosilicates.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium also occurs in the minerals beryl, cryolite, garnet, spinel, and turquoise.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Impurities in alumina yield gemstones: for example, chromium yields ruby and iron yields sapphire.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Native aluminium metal is extremely rare and can only be found as a minor phase in low oxygen fugacity environments, such as the interiors of certain volcanoes.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Native aluminium has been reported in cold seeps in the northeastern continental slope of the South China Sea.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] It is possible that these deposits resulted from bacterial reduction of tetrahydroxoaluminate Al(OH)4−.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Although aluminium is a common and widespread element, not all aluminium minerals are economically viable sources of the metal.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Almost all metallic aluminium is produced from the ore bauxite (AlO*x*(OH)3–2*x*).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Bauxite occurs as a weathering product of low iron and silica bedrock in tropical climatic conditions.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] In 2017, most bauxite was mined in Australia, China, Guinea, and India.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The history of aluminium has been shaped by usage of alum.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The first written record of alum, made by Greek historian Herodotus, dates back to the 5th century BCE.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The ancients are known to have used alum as a dyeing mordant and for city defense as a fire-resistant coating for wood.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] After the Crusades, alum, an indispensable good in the European fabric industry, was a subject of international commerce; it was imported to Europe from the eastern Mediterranean until the mid-15th century.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The nature of alum remained unknown until Swiss physician Paracelsus suggested alum was a salt of an earth of alum around 1530.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] German doctor and chemist Andreas Libavius experimentally confirmed this in 1595.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] German chemist Friedrich Hoffmann announced his belief that the base of alum was a distinct earth in 1722.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] German chemist Andreas Sigismund Marggraf synthesized alumina in 1754 by boiling clay in sulfuric acid and subsequently adding potash.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Attempts to produce aluminium date back to 1760.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The first successful attempt, however, was completed in 1824 by Danish physicist and chemist Hans Christian Ørsted.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] He reacted anhydrous aluminium chloride with potassium amalgam, yielding a lump of metal looking similar to tin.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] He presented his results and demonstrated a sample of the new metal in 1825.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] In 1827, German chemist Friedrich Wöhler repeated Ørsted's experiments but did not identify any aluminium.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] (The reason for this inconsistency was only discovered in 1921.) He conducted a similar experiment in the same year by mixing anhydrous aluminium chloride with potassium (the Wöhler process) and produced a powder of aluminium.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] In 1845, he was able to produce small pieces of the metal and described some physical properties of this metal.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] For many years thereafter, Wöhler was credited as the discoverer of aluminium.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] As Wöhler's method could not yield great quantities of aluminium, the metal remained rare; its cost exceeded that of gold.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The first industrial production of aluminium was established in 1856 by French chemist Henri Étienne Sainte-Claire Deville and companions.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Sainte-Claire Deville had discovered that aluminium trichloride could be reduced by sodium, which was more convenient and less expensive than potassium, which Wöhler had used.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Even then, aluminium was still not of great purity and produced aluminium differed in properties by sample.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Because of its electricity-conducting capacity, aluminium was used as the cap of the Washington Monument, completed in 1885, the tallest building in the world at the time.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The non-corroding metal cap was intended to serve as a lightning rod peak.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The first industrial large-scale production method was independently developed in 1886 by French engineer Paul Héroult and American engineer Charles Martin Hall; it is now known as the Hall–Héroult process.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The Hall–Héroult process converts alumina into metal.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Austrian chemist Carl Joseph Bayer discovered a way of purifying bauxite to yield alumina, now known as the Bayer process, in 1889.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Modern production of aluminium is based on the Bayer and Hall–Héroult processes.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] As large-scale production caused aluminium prices to drop, the metal became widely used in jewelry, eyeglass frames, optical instruments, tableware, and foil, and other everyday items in the 1890s and early 20th century.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium's ability to form hard yet light alloys with other metals provided the metal with many uses at the time.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] During World War I, major governments demanded large shipments of aluminium for light strong airframes; during World War II, demand by major governments for aviation was even higher.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] From the early 20th century to 1980, the aluminium industry was characterized by cartelization, as aluminium firms colluded to keep prices high and stable.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The first aluminium cartel, the Aluminium Association, was founded in 1901 by the Pittsburgh Reduction Company (renamed Alcoa in 1907) and Aluminium Industrie AG.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The British Aluminium Company, Produits Chimiques d'Alais et de la Camargue, and Société Électro-Métallurgique de Froges also joined the cartel.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] By the mid-20th century, aluminium had become a part of everyday life and an essential component of housewares.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] In 1954, production of aluminium surpassed that of copper, historically second in production only to iron, making it the most produced non-ferrous metal.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] During the mid-20th century, aluminium emerged as a civil engineering material, with building applications in both basic construction and interior finish work, and increasingly being used in military engineering, for both airplanes and armored vehicle engines.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Earth's first artificial satellite, launched in 1957, consisted of two separate aluminium semi-spheres joined and all subsequent space vehicles have used aluminium to some extent.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The aluminium can was invented in 1956 and employed as a storage for drinks in 1958.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Throughout the 20th century, the production of aluminium rose rapidly: while the world production of aluminium in 1900 was 6,800 metric tons, the annual production first exceeded 100,000 metric tons in 1916; 1,000,000 tons in 1941; 10,000,000 tons in 1971.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] In the 1970s, the increased demand for aluminium made it an exchange commodity; it entered the London Metal Exchange, the oldest industrial metal exchange in the world, in 1978.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The output continued to grow: the annual production of aluminium exceeded 50,000,000 metric tons in 2013.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The real price for aluminium declined from $14,000 per metric ton in 1900 to $2,340 in 1948 (in 1998 United States dollars).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Extraction and processing costs were lowered over technological progress and the scale of the economies.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] However, the need to exploit lower-grade poorer quality deposits and the use of fast increasing input costs (above all, energy) increased the net cost of aluminium; the real price began to grow in the 1970s with the rise of energy cost.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Production moved from the industrialized countries to countries where production was cheaper.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Production costs in the late 20th century changed because of advances in technology, lower energy prices, exchange rates of the United States dollar, and alumina prices.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The BRIC countries' combined share in primary production and primary consumption grew substantially in the first decade of the 21st century.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] China is accumulating an especially large share of the world's production thanks to an abundance of resources, cheap energy, and governmental stimuli; it also increased its consumption share from 2% in 1972 to 40% in 2010.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] In the United States, Western Europe, and Japan, most aluminium was consumed in transportation, engineering, construction, and packaging.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] In 2021, prices for industrial metals such as aluminium have soared to near-record levels as energy shortages in China drive up costs for electricity.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The names *aluminium* and *aluminum* are derived from the word *alumine*, an obsolete term for *alumina*, the primary naturally occurring oxide of aluminium.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] *Alumine* was borrowed from French, which in turn derived it from *alumen*, the classical Latin name for alum, the mineral from which it was collected.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The Latin word *alumen* stems from the Proto-Indo-European root **alu-* meaning "bitter" or "beer".
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The English name *alum* does not come directly from Latin, whereas *alumine*/*alumina* comes from the Latin word *alumen* (on declension, *alumen* changes to *alumin-*).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] British chemist Humphry Davy, who performed a number of experiments aimed to isolate the metal, is credited as the person who named the element.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The first name proposed for the metal to be isolated from alum was *alumium*, which Davy suggested in an 1808 article on his electrochemical research, published in Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] It appeared that the name was created from the English word *alum* and the Latin suffix *-ium*; but it was customary then to give elements names originating in Latin, so this name was not adopted universally.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The name *alumium* was criticized by contemporary chemists from France, Germany, and Sweden, who insisted the metal should be named for the oxide, alumina, from which it would be isolated.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] One example was *Essai sur la Nomenclature chimique* (July 1811), written in French by a Swedish chemist, Jöns Jacob Berzelius, in which the name *aluminium* is given to the element that would be synthesized from alum.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] (Another article in the same journal issue also refers to the metal whose oxide is the basis of sapphire, i.e., the same metal, as to *aluminium*.) A January 1811 summary of one of Davy's lectures at the Royal Society mentioned the name *aluminium* as a possibility.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] In 1812, Davy published his chemistry text *Elements of Chemical Philosophy* in which he used the spelling *aluminum*.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] In 1812, British scientist Thomas Young wrote an anonymous review of Davy's book, in which he proposed the name *aluminium* instead of *aluminum*, which he thought had a "less classical sound".
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] This name persisted: although the *-um* spelling was occasionally used in Britain, the American scientific language used *-ium* from the start.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The French have used the spelling *aluminium* from the start.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Most scientists throughout the world used *-ium* in the 19th century; and it was entrenched in several other European languages, such as French, German, and Dutch.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] In 1828, an American lexicographer, Noah Webster, entered only the *aluminum* spelling in his *American Dictionary of the English Language*.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] In the 1830s, the *-um* spelling gained usage in the United States; by the 1860s, it had become the more common spelling there outside science.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] In 1892, Hall used the *-um* spelling in his advertising handbill for his new electrolytic method of producing the metal, despite his constant use of the *-ium* spelling in all the patents he filed between 1886 and 1903.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] It is unknown whether this spelling was introduced by mistake or intentionally, but Hall preferred *aluminum* since its introduction because it resembled *platinum*, the name of a prestigious metal.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] By 1890, both spellings had been common in the United States, the *-ium* spelling being slightly more common; by 1895, the situation had reversed; by 1900, *aluminum* had become twice as common as *aluminium*; in the next decade, the *-um* spelling dominated American usage.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] In 1925, the American Chemical Society adopted the spelling *aluminum*.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) adopted *aluminium* as the standard international name for the element in 1990.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] In 1993, they recognized *aluminum* as an acceptable variant; the most recent 2005 edition of the IUPAC nomenclature of inorganic chemistry also acknowledges this spelling.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] IUPAC official publications use the *-ium* spelling as primary, and they list both where it is appropriate.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Their usage is currently regional: *aluminum* dominates in the United States and Canada; *aluminium* is prevalent in the rest of the English-speaking world.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] German physicist Ludwig Wilhelm Gilbert had proposed *Thonerde-metall*, after the German *Thonerde* for alumina, in his *Annalen der Physik* but that name never caught on at all even in Germany.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Richards in 1891 found just one occurrence of *argillium* in Swedish, from the French *argille* for clay.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The production of aluminium starts with the extraction of bauxite rock from the ground.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The bauxite is processed and transformed using the Bayer process into alumina, which is then processed using the Hall–Héroult process, resulting in the final aluminium.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium production is highly energy-consuming, and so the producers tend to locate smelters in places where electric power is both plentiful and inexpensive.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Production of one kilogram of aluminium requires 7 kilograms of oil energy equivalent, as compared to 1.5 kilograms for steel and 2 kilograms for plastic.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] As of 2024, the world's largest producers of aluminium were China, India, Russia, Canada, and the United Arab Emirates, while China is by far the top producer of aluminium with a world share of over 55%.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] According to the International Resource Panel's Metal Stocks in Society report, the global per capita stock of aluminium in use in society (i.e. in cars, buildings, electronics, etc.) is 80 kg (180 lb).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Much of this is in more-developed countries (350–500 kg (770–1,100 lb) per capita) rather than less-developed countries (35 kg (77 lb) per capita).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Bauxite is converted to alumina by the Bayer process.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Bauxite is blended for uniform composition and then is ground fine.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] After this reaction, the slurry is at a temperature above its atmospheric boiling point.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] It is cooled by removing steam as pressure is reduced.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The bauxite residue is separated from the solution and discarded.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The solution, free of solids, is seeded with small crystals of aluminium hydroxide; this causes decomposition of the [Al(OH)4]− ions to aluminium hydroxide.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] After about half of aluminium has precipitated, the mixture is sent to classifiers.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Small crystals of aluminium hydroxide are collected to serve as seeding agents; coarse particles are converted to alumina by heating; the excess solution is removed by evaporation, (if needed) purified, and recycled.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The conversion of alumina to aluminium is achieved by the Hall–Héroult process.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] In this energy-intensive process, a solution of alumina in a molten (940 and 970 °C (1,720 and 1,780 °F)) mixture of cryolite (Na3AlF6) with calcium fluoride is electrolyzed to produce metallic aluminium.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The liquid aluminium sinks to the bottom of the solution and is tapped off, and usually cast into large blocks called aluminium billets for further processing.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Anodes of the electrolysis cell are made of carbon—the most resistant material against fluoride corrosion—and either bake at the process or are prebaked.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The former, also called Söderberg anodes, are less power-efficient and fumes released during baking are costly to collect, which is why they are being replaced by prebaked anodes even though they save the power, energy, and labor to prebake the cathodes.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Carbon for anodes should be preferably pure so that neither aluminium nor the electrolyte is contaminated with ash.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Despite carbon's resistivity against corrosion, it is still consumed at a rate of 0.4–0.5 kg per each kilogram of produced aluminium.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Cathodes are made of anthracite; high purity for them is not required because impurities leach only very slowly.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The cathode is consumed at a rate of 0.02–0.04 kg per each kilogram of produced aluminium.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] A cell is usually terminated after 2–6 years following a failure of the cathode.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The Hall–Heroult process produces aluminium with a purity of above 99%.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Further purification can be done by the Hoopes process.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] This process involves the electrolysis of molten aluminium with a sodium, barium, and aluminium fluoride electrolyte.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The resulting aluminium has a purity of 99.99%.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Electric power represents about 20 to 40% of the cost of producing aluminium, depending on the location of the smelter.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium production consumes roughly 5% of electricity generated in the United States.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Because of this, alternatives to the Hall–Héroult process have been researched, but none has turned out to be economically feasible.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Recovery of the metal through recycling has become an important task of the aluminium industry.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Recycling was a low-profile activity until the late 1960s, when the growing use of aluminium beverage cans brought it to public awareness.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Recycling involves melting the scrap, a process that requires only 5% of the energy used to produce aluminium from ore, though a significant part (up to 15% of the input material) is lost as dross (ash-like oxide).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] An aluminium stack melter produces significantly less dross, with values reported below 1%.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] White dross from primary aluminium production and from secondary recycling operations still contains useful quantities of aluminium that can be extracted industrially.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The process produces aluminium billets, together with a highly complex waste material.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] It reacts with water, releasing a mixture of gases including, among others, acetylene, hydrogen sulfide and significant amounts of ammonia.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Despite these difficulties, the waste is used as a filler in asphalt and concrete.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Its potential for hydrogen production has also been considered and researched.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The global production of aluminium in 2016 was 58.8 million metric tons.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] It exceeded that of any other metal except iron (1,231 million metric tons).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is almost always alloyed, which markedly improves its mechanical properties, especially when tempered.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] For example, the common aluminium foils and beverage cans are alloys of 92% to 99% aluminium.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The main alloying agents for both wrought and cast aluminium are copper, zinc, magnesium, manganese, and silicon (e.g., duralumin) with the levels of other metals in a few percent by weight.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is the main substitute to copper and its applications to the traditional domains of copper have seen increased interest when copper prices are high such as in 2011–2014 and 2021.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] There is a competition in the use of aluminium and copper in the automotive industry, but in other uses such as in the construction industry and in underground and submarine cables aluminium has been largely unable to compete with copper.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The great majority (about 90%) of aluminium oxide is converted to metallic aluminium.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Being a very hard material (Mohs hardness 9), alumina is widely used as an abrasive; being extraordinarily chemically inert, it is useful in highly reactive environments such as high pressure sodium lamps.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium oxide is commonly used as a catalyst for industrial processes; e.g. the Claus process to convert hydrogen sulfide to sulfur in refineries and to alkylate amines.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Many industrial catalysts are supported by alumina, meaning that the expensive catalyst material is dispersed over a surface of the inert alumina.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Another principal use is as a drying agent or absorbent.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Several sulfates of aluminium have industrial and commercial application.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium sulfate (in its hydrate form) is produced on the annual scale of several millions of metric tons.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] About two-thirds is consumed in water treatment.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] The next major application is in the manufacture of paper.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] It is also used as a mordant in dyeing, in pickling seeds, deodorizing of mineral oils, in leather tanning, and in production of other aluminium compounds.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Two kinds of alum, ammonium alum and potassium alum, were formerly used as mordants and in leather tanning, but their use has significantly declined following availability of high-purity aluminium sulfate.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Anhydrous aluminium chloride is used as a catalyst in chemical and petrochemical industries, the dyeing industry, and in synthesis of various inorganic and organic compounds.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium hydroxychlorides are used in purifying water, in the paper industry, and as antiperspirants.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p01] Sodium aluminate is used in treating water and as an accelerator of solidification of cement.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] Despite its widespread occurrence in the Earth's crust, aluminium has no known function in biology.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] At pH 6–9 (relevant for most natural waters), aluminium precipitates out of water as the hydroxide and is hence not available; most elements behaving this way have no biological role or are toxic.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] Aluminium sulfate has an LD50 of 6207 mg/kg (oral, mouse).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] Aluminium is classified as a non-carcinogen by the United States Department of Health and Human Services.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] A review published in 1988 said that there was little evidence that normal exposure to aluminium presents a risk to healthy adult, and a 2014 multi-element toxicology review was unable to find deleterious effects of aluminium consumed in amounts not greater than 40 mg/day per kg of body mass.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] Most ingested aluminium is eliminated in feces, and much of what enters the bloodstream is excreted in urine; however, not all absorbed or parenterally administered aluminium is cleared through urinary excretion.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] Aluminium, although rarely, can cause vitamin D-resistant osteomalacia, erythropoietin-resistant microcytic anemia, and central nervous system alterations.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] People with kidney insufficiency are especially at a risk.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] Chronic ingestion of hydrated aluminium silicates (for excess gastric acidity control) may result in aluminium binding to intestinal contents and increased elimination of other metals, such as iron or zinc; sufficiently high doses (>50 g/day) can cause anemia.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] During the 1988 Camelford water pollution incident, people in Camelford had their drinking water contaminated with aluminium sulfate for several weeks.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] A final report into the incident in 2013 concluded it was unlikely that this had caused long-term health problems.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] Aluminium has been suspected of being a possible cause of Alzheimer's disease, but research into this for over 40 years has found, as of 2018, no good evidence of causal effect.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] Aluminium increases estrogen-related gene expression in human breast cancer cells cultured in the laboratory.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] In very high doses, aluminium is associated with altered function of the blood–brain barrier.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] A small percentage of people have contact allergies to aluminium and experience itchy red rashes, headache, muscle pain, joint pain, poor memory, insomnia, depression, asthma, irritable bowel syndrome, or other symptoms upon contact with products containing aluminium.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] Exposure to powdered aluminium or aluminium welding fumes can cause pulmonary fibrosis.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] Fine aluminium powder can ignite or explode, posing another workplace hazard.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] Drinking water contains more aluminium than solid food; however, aluminium in food may be absorbed more than aluminium from water.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] Dietary exposure in Europeans averages to 0.2–1.5 mg/kg/week but can be as high as 2.3 mg/kg/week.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] Higher exposure levels of aluminium are mostly limited to plumbers, masons, electrical workers, machinists, and surgeons.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] Consumption of antacids, antiperspirants, vaccines, and cosmetics provide possible routes of exposure.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] Consumption of acidic foods or liquids with aluminium enhances aluminium absorption, and maltol has been shown to increase the accumulation of aluminium in nerve and bone tissues.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] In case of suspected sudden intake of a large amount of aluminium, the only treatment is deferoxamine mesylate which may be given to help eliminate aluminium from the body by chelation therapy.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] However, this should be applied with caution as this reduces not only aluminium body levels, but also those of other metals such as copper or iron.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] High levels of aluminium occur near mining sites; small amounts of aluminium are released to the environment at coal-fired power plants or incinerators.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] Aluminium in the air is washed out by the rain or normally settles down but small particles of aluminium remain in the air for a long time.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] Acidic precipitation is the main natural factor to mobilize aluminium from natural sources and the main reason for the environmental effects of aluminium; however, the main factor of presence of aluminium in salt and freshwater are the industrial processes that also release aluminium into air.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] In water, aluminium acts as a toxic agent on gill-breathing animals such as fish when the water is acidic, in which aluminium may precipitate on gills, which causes loss of plasma- and hemolymph ions leading to osmoregulatory failure.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] Organic complexes of aluminium may be easily absorbed and interfere with metabolism in mammals and birds, even though this rarely happens in practice.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] Aluminium is primary among the factors that reduce plant growth on acidic soils.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] Although it is generally harmless to plant growth in pH-neutral soils, in acid soils the concentration of toxic Al3+ cations increases and disturbs root growth and function.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] Wheat has developed a tolerance to aluminium, releasing organic compounds that bind to harmful aluminium cations.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] Sorghum is believed to have the same tolerance mechanism.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] Aluminium production possesses its own challenges to the environment on each step of the production process.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] The major challenge is the emission of greenhouse gases.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] These gases result from electrical consumption of the smelters and the byproducts of processing.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] The most potent of these gases are perfluorocarbons, namely CF4 and C2F6, from the smelting process.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] Biodegradation of metallic aluminium is extremely rare; most aluminium-corroding organisms do not directly attack or consume the aluminium, but instead produce corrosive wastes.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] The fungus *Geotrichum candidum* can consume the aluminium in compact discs.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/aluminum-p02] The bacterium *Pseudomonas aeruginosa* and the fungus *Cladosporium resinae* are commonly detected in aircraft fuel tanks that use kerosene-based fuels (not avgas), and laboratory cultures can degrade aluminium.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/astron-2-6] The **Mitsubishi Astron** or **4G5/4D5 engine**, is a series of straight-four internal combustion engines first built by Mitsubishi Motors in 1972.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/astron-2-6] Engine displacement ranged from 1.8 to 2.6 litres, making it one of the largest four-cylinder engines of its time.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/astron-2-6] It employed a hemispherical cylinder head, chain-driven single overhead camshaft (SOHC) and eight valves (two per cylinder).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/astron-2-6] United States passenger car versions had a small secondary intake valve referred to as the "Jet Valve".
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/astron-2-6] This valve induced swirl in the intake charge, enabling the use of leaner fuel/air mixtures for lower emissions.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/astron-2-6] It was designed as a cartridge containing the valve spring and seat which simply screwed into a threaded hole in the head, similar to a spark plug but inside the cam cover.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/astron-2-6] The rocker arms for the intake valve were widened on the valve end to accommodate the cartridge, which was equipped with a very soft valve spring in order to avoid wear on the camshaft intake lobe.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/astron-2-6] Modifications to the head were thereby reduced as the Jet Valve negated the necessity for a three-valve-per-cylinder design.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/astron-2-6] In 1975, the *Astron 80* introduced a system dubbed "Silent Shaft": the first use of twin balance shafts in a modern engine.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/astron-2-6] It followed the designs of Frederick Lanchester, whose original patents Mitsubishi had obtained, and proved influential as Fiat/Lancia, Saab and Porsche all licensed this technology.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/astron-2-6] The **4D5 engine** is a range of four-cylinder belt-driven overhead camshaft diesel engines which were part of the "Astron" family, and introduced in 1980 in the then new fifth generation Galant.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/astron-2-6] As the first turbodiesel to be offered in a Japanese passenger car, it proved popular in the emerging SUV and minivan markets where Mitsubishi was highly successful, until superseded by the 4M4 range in 1993.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/astron-2-6] However, production of the 4D5 (4D56) continued throughout the 1990s as a lower-cost option than the more modern powerplants.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/astron-2-6] Until now it is still in production, but made into a modern powerplant by putting a common rail direct injection fuel system into the engine.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/astron-2-6] Peak power for a 1975 Canter is 100 PS (74 kW), but power increased to as much as 125 PS (92 kW) for the twin-carb version fitted to the Galant GTO GSR and A115 Galant GS-II.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/astron-2-6] In Australia this engine was used in the Sigma, Scorpion and L200.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/astron-2-6] Peak power is 110 PS (81 kW) at 5000 rpm, as fitted to the Rosa bus or the Canter cabover truck.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/astron-2-6] This engine shares its dimensions with the contemporary Fuso 4DR1 diesel engine.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/astron-2-6] The G54B for the US market had a cylinder head with additional jet valves to improve emissions (MCA-Jet system).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/astron-2-6] The engine was fitted to various Mitsubishi models from 1978 to 1997 and to the American Chrysler K-cars and their derivatives between 1981 and 1987.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/astron-2-6] It was primarily set up longitudinally for use in rear-wheel drive and all-wheel drive platforms but also as a transverse engine in the front-wheel drive platform of the Mitsubishi Magna and Chrysler K platform.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/astron-2-6] Chrysler commonly marketed the engine "Hemi," whereas the Australian-made version was marketed as the "Astron II" and featured "Balance Shaft" technology, which was subsequently licensed to Porsche and other automakers.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/astron-2-6] The original engine featured a Mikuni two-barrel carburetor with a secondary vacuum actuator; later versions adopted EFI.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/astron-2-6] Chrysler commonly paired this engine with its A470 3-speed automatic transmission; in Australia, Mitsubishi adapted it to a 5-speed manual transmission and its "ELC" (Electronic Control) 4-speed automatic transmission, featuring electronic overdrive.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/astron-2-6] Chrysler eventually replaced the 4G54 with its own 2.5 L engine, whereas Mitsubishi replaced it with a 2.4 L engine codenamed 4G64.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/astron-2-6] Single two-Venturi downdraught carburetor.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/astron-2-6] This engine is also built by Hyundai in South Korea, meaning it also sees use in some products made by their Kia subsidiary.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/astron-2-6] Hyundai calls it the **D4BA/D4BX** (normally aspirated), **D4BF** (non-intercooled turbo), or **D4BH** (intercooled turbo).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/auto-show] An **auto show**, also known as a **motor show** or **car show**, is a public exhibition of current automobile models, debuts, concept cars, or out-of-production classics.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/auto-show] It is attended by automotive industry representatives, dealers, auto journalists and car enthusiasts.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/auto-show] Most auto shows occur once or twice a year.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/auto-show] They are important to car manufacturers and local dealers as a public relations exercise, as they advertise new products and promote auto brands.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/auto-show] The five most prestigious auto shows, sometimes called the "**Big Five**", are generally considered to be held in Detroit, Frankfurt, Geneva, Paris and Tokyo.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/auto-show] Car enthusiast communities along the historic U.S.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/auto-show] Some auto shows have more than just cars including: all sorts of other vehicles.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/auto-show] The types of vehicles can include buses, trucks and almost any other types of vehicles such as Auto Expo in Delhi brings a variety of vehicles ranging from private to commercial.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/auto-show] The International Organization of Motor Vehicle Manufacturers organizes many auto shows, including the Big Five.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/auto-show] These shows all have an advertising purpose.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/auto-show] They are held as part of the sales strategy of the manufacturers.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/auto-show] There are other car shows that are organized by car enthusiast associations, automobile dealers, retail businesses, charitable organizations, or municipalities.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/auto-show] There is no generally accepted term for these more common events.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/auto-show] Manufacturer car shows typically showcase vehicles currently being manufactured and available for purchase.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/auto-show] Enthusiast car shows showcase individually owned vehicles, that are not currently being manufactured, and that are not available for purchase.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/auto-show] Enthusiast car shows usually draw their entries locally.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/auto-show] There are many car shows in various localities across many nations.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] The **automotive industry** comprises a wide range of companies and organisations involved in the design, development, manufacturing, marketing, selling, repairing, and modification of motor vehicles.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] It is one of the world's largest industries by revenue with global automotive market at ~$2.75 trillion in 2025.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] The word *automotive* comes from the Greek *autos* (self), and Latin *motivus* (of motion), referring to any form of self-powered vehicle.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] This term, as proposed by Elmer Sperry (1860–1930), first came into use to describe automobiles in 1898.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] The automotive industry began in the 1860s with hundreds of manufacturers pioneering the horseless carriage.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] Early car manufacturing involved manual assembly by a human worker.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] The process evolved from engineers working on a stationary car to a conveyor belt system where the car passed through multiple stations of more specialised engineers.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] In the 1960s, robotic equipment was introduced, and most cars are now mainly assembled by automated machinery.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] For many decades, the United States led the world in total automobile production, with the U.S.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] Big Three General Motors, Ford Motor Company, and Chrysler being the world's three largest auto manufacturers for a time, and G.M. and Ford remaining the two largest until the mid-2000s.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] In 1929, before the Great Depression, the world had 32,028,500 automobiles in use, of which the U.S. automobile enterprises produced more than 90%.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] At that time, the U.S. had one car per 4.87 persons.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] After 1945, the U.S. produced around three-quarters of the world's auto production.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] In 1980, the U.S. was overtaken by Japan and then became a world leader again in 1994.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] Japan narrowly passed the U.S. in production during 2006 and 2007, and in 2008 also China, which in 2009 took the top spot (from Japan) with 13.8 million units, although the U.S. surpassed Japan in 2011, to become the second-largest automobile industry.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] In 2024, China produced more than 31 million vehicles in a year, after breaking 30 million in 2023, reaching 29 million for the first time in 2017 and 28 million the year before.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] In 2024, China produced the most passenger cars in the world, with Japan, India, Germany, and South Korea trailing.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] This was achieved by Chinese car companies signing joint ventures with foreign manufacturers.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] From 1970 (140 models) to 1998 (260 models) to 2012 (684 models), the number of automobile models in the U.S. has grown nearly twofold.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] Safety is a state that implies being protected from any risk, danger, damage, or cause of injury.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] In the automotive industry, safety means that users, operators, or manufacturers do not face any risk or danger coming from the motor vehicle or its spare parts.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] Safety for the automobiles themselves implies that there is no risk of damage.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] Safety in the automotive industry is particularly important and therefore highly regulated.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] Automobiles and other motor vehicles have to comply with a certain number of regulations, whether local or international, in order to be accepted on the market.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] The standard ISO 26262, is considered one of the best practice frameworks for achieving automotive functional safety.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] In case of safety issues, danger, product defect, or faulty procedure during the manufacturing of the motor vehicle, the maker can request to return either a batch or the entire production run.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] This procedure is called product recall.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] Product recalls happen in every industry and can be production-related or stem from raw materials.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] Product and operation tests and inspections at different stages of the value chain are made to avoid these product recalls by ensuring end-user security and safety and compliance with the automotive industry requirements.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] However, the automotive industry is still particularly concerned about product recalls, which cause considerable financial consequences.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] In 2007, there were about 806 million cars and light trucks on the road, consuming over 980 billion litres (980,000,000 m3) of petrol and diesel fuel yearly.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] The automobile is a primary mode of transportation for many developed economies.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] The Detroit branch of Boston Consulting Group predicted that, by 2014, one-third of world demand would be in the four BRIC markets (Brazil, Russia, India, and China).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] Meanwhile, in developed countries, the automotive industry has slowed.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] It is also expected that this trend will continue, especially as the younger generations of people (in highly urbanised countries) no longer want to own a car, and prefer other modes of transport.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] Other potentially powerful automotive markets are Iran and Indonesia.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] Emerging automobile markets already buy more cars than established markets.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] Power study, emerging markets accounted for 51 percent of the global light-vehicle sales in 2010.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] The study, performed in 2010 expected this trend to accelerate.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] However, more recent reports (2012) confirmed the opposite; namely that the automotive industry was slowing down even in BRIC countries.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] In the United States, vehicle sales peaked in 2000, at 17.8 million units.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] In July 2021, the European Commission released its "Fit for 55" legislation package, which contains important guidelines for the future of the automotive industry; all new cars on the European market must be zero-emission vehicles from 2035.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] The governments of 24 developed countries and a group of major car manufacturers including GM, Ford, Volvo, BYD Auto, Jaguar Land Rover and Mercedes-Benz committed to "work towards all sales of new cars and vans being zero emission globally by 2040, and by no later than 2035 in leading markets".
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] Major car manufacturing nations like the United States, Germany, China, Japan and South Korea, as well as Volkswagen, Toyota, Peugeot, Honda, Nissan and Hyundai, did not pledge.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] The global automotive industry is a major consumer of water.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] Some estimates surpass 180,000 L (39,000 imp gal) of water per car manufactured, depending on whether tyre production is included.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] Production processes that use a significant volume of water include surface treatment, painting, coating, washing, cooling, air-conditioning, and boilers, not counting component manufacturing.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] Paintshop operations consume especially large amounts of water because equipment running on water-based products must also be cleaned with water.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] In 2022, Tesla's Gigafactory Berlin-Brandenburg ran into legal challenges due to droughts and falling groundwater levels in the region.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] Brandenburg's Economy Minister Joerg Steinbach said that while water supply was sufficient during the first stage, more would be needed once Tesla expands the site.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] The factory would nearly double the water consumption in the Gruenheide area, with 1.4 million cubic meters being contracted from local authorities per year — enough for a city of around 40,000 people.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] Steinbach said that the authorities would like to drill for more water there and outsource any additional supply if necessary.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] : US had produced more than 80% of motor vehicles.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] : India overtakes Germany to become 4th largest automobile producer.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] The OICA counts over 50 countries that assemble, manufacture, or disseminate automobiles.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] Of those, only 15 countries (**boldfaced** in the list below) currently possess the capability to design original production automobiles from the ground up, and 17 countries (listed below) have at least one million produced vehicles a year (as of 2023).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] All ten remained as the ten largest car makers by sales until the merger between Fiat-Chrysler and the PSA Group in early 2021; only Renault was degraded to 11th place, in 2022, when being surpassed by both BMW (which became the 10th largest in 2021) and Chang'an.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] The eighteen largest as of 2013 have remained in the top 20 as of 2017, except Mitsubishi which fell out of top 20 in 2016, while Geely fell out of the top 20 in 2014 and 2015 but re-entered it in 2016.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] Mercedes-Benz Group held a combined 6.2% stake in the Renault–Nissan–Mitsubishi Alliance, and the Renault-Nissan-Mitsubishi Alliance also held a combined 6.2% stake in Mercedes-Benz Group until 2021.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] Until 2022, China required foreign automotive firms to form joint ventures in order to access their market.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/automotive-industry] The policy led to quality improvement across the industry.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] Cunningham Company** was an American automobile company established by Briggs Cunningham.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] It produced six different models in very small numbers, primarily to be raced at the 24 Hours of Le Mans.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] In 1949 Briggs Cunningham met Phil Walters, who raced Midgets and Stock cars under the nom de course "Ted Tappet".
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] Walters began driving for Cunningham, taking the wheel of the latter's Cadillac-powered Healey Silverstone the following year.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] Walters was also a partner with Bill Frick in Frick-Tappet Motors, which had started out as a Volkswagen and Porsche dealership but had begun building auto conversions called "Fordillacs" by installing new Cadillac V8 engines into 1949 Ford chassis.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] Cunningham bought a Fordillac after seeing one at a hill-climb, planning to enter it in the 1950 24 Hours of Le Mans.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] The Fordillac was rejected by the Le Mans organizers due to its engine swap, so instead Cunningham entered two cars based on the Cadillac Series 61.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] The first was dubbed "Petit Pataud" by the French in a possible reference to a puppy in a French children's book from the 1930s.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] This car's appearance was essentially stock, with changes that included a dual-carburetor intake manifold, brake cooling ducts, a second fuel tank, and extra lights.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] While engine swaps were illegal, body modifications were permitted, so the second car had its stock body removed and a new aluminum body fabricated over a metal tube framework.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] The custom body, lower and narrower than stock, was designed and built with the help of engineer Howard Weinmann from Grumman.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] Another feature was the use of five carburetors.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] Designer and bodywork specialist Bob Blake was hurriedly brought in to repair "Petit Pataud" when it was damaged in a pre-race shunt with "Le Monstre".
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] Cunningham and remained responsible for building the cars until 1955.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] Brothers Cowles "Miles" Collier and Sam Collier partnered to drive "Petit Pataud", and finished in tenth place.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] Cunningham and co-driver Walters were in "Le Monstre", and finished one place behind the other Cadillac in eleventh place.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] In preparation for his next attempt at Le Mans, Cunningham bought the Frick-Tappett Motors company.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] The operation was moved from Long Island, New York to West Palm Beach, Florida, and renamed the "B.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] After fielding cars at Circuit de la Sarthe from 1951 to 1955, several of the Cunningham racing team retired following the 1955 Le Mans disaster.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] 1955 also marked the end of the grace period the American Internal Revenue Service allowed for a company to become profitable.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] With few cars having been built and no profits to show, the IRS reclassified the B.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] Cunningham Company as a hobby, meaning that the racing and production expenses were no longer tax deductible.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] Briggs Cunningham wound up the operation and sold the West Palm Beach factory.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] An attempt at reviving the company was made in 2001 under Bob Lutz and Briggs Cunningham III (son of the company founder), although production did not commence.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] The first product of the new company was the Cunningham C-1 roadster.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] On the design team were Cunningham, Walters, G.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] Only one C-1 was built, with serial number 5101.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] The car was completed in late 1950, and is generally listed as from the 1951 model year.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] The chassis was made of 3 in (76 mm) steel tubing with a central X-brace.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] The rear suspension was a custom-made De Dion tube.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] The tires were mounted on knock-off wire wheels.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] Wheelbase was 105 in (2,667 mm), and the track front and rear was 58 in (1,473 mm).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] The engine was a 331 cu in (5,424 cc) Cadillac V8.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] The C-1 was used in practice at Le Mans, but did not race.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] In 1951 it appeared at the Mount Equinox hillclimb, where it finished fourth driven by John Fitch.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] The C-1 was followed by the C-2, of which three were built, all to racing specifications and so called C-2R.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] The C-2R's front suspension used Ford parts, while the rear suspension had Oldsmobile springs and the brake system used Cadillac components.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] Unable to secure a supply of the Cadillac engine, Cunningham substituted a version of the Chrysler FirePower V8 in the C-2R.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] All three cars were entered, driven by teams John Fitch and Phil Walters, George Rand and Fred Wacker Jr., and Briggs Cunningham and George Huntoon.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] The best finish was eighteenth, for the Fitch/Walters car.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] To have his namesake cars homologated as a manufacturer for Le Mans, Cunningham undertook to build 25 examples of the C-3 road car.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] The C-3 also used the 331 cu in (5,424 cc) Chrysler FirePower V8, but with a new intake manifold with four Zenith 1-bbl carburetors, and a dual exhaust system.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] Power was raised to 220 hp (164.1 kW) from the factory version's 180 hp (134.2 kW).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] Two different transmissions were offered; a three-speed manual from Cadillac, or Chrysler's Presto-Matic semi-automatic fluid-coupled two-speed with electric overdrive, for an effective selection of four forward ratios.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] The C-3's large-diameter tube chassis was similar to that of the earlier C-2, but the C-2's De Dion tube gave way to a coil-spring live axle located by upper and lower trailing arms on each side.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] Two pre-production cars similar in appearance to the C-2Rs were completed in West Palm Beach; a roadster with chassis number 5205, and a coupe with chassis number 5206X.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] A third chassis, number 5206, was sent to the workshops of carrozzeria Vignale in Turin, Italy, where it received a new coupe body styled by designer Giovanni Michelotti, then working at Vignale.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] The factory considered chassis 5206 the official prototype, and subsequent cars received the Michelotti body style.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] One reference reports eighteen coupes and nine convertibles.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] Others report twenty coupes and five convertibles with bodies by Vignale, plus the two cars bodied at the West Palm Beach factory.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] The New York Museum of Modern Art named the C-3 Continental Coupé one of the "10 Best Contemporary Automobiles".
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] By the time development of the C-4R started, Bill Frick had left the company.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] During the car's development the team was also joined by mechanic and bodyman Herbert "Bud" Unger, who did the bodywork for the C-4R and C-5R.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] The De Dion tube rear suspension was also gone.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] Although a new independent rear suspension of Cunningham's own design was touted early in the car's development, it seems that later a live axle on coil springs was substituted.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] Also new was a Cunningham-designed 5-speed manual transmission.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] Brakes were Chrysler Al-Fin units twenty percent larger than those on the C-2Rs, and the earlier car's wire wheels had been replaced with knock-off Halibrand magnesium wheels.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] To provide Cunningham's cars with more power from their FirePower engine, Chrysler engineers John Platner and Don Moore began an engine development project called A311.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] In its ultimate form the A311 engine used a gear-driven, high-lift long-duration camshaft, special pistons, roller tappets, dual valve springs, special pushrods, Hilborn fuel injection with tuned intake stacks, and a compression ratio of 12:1.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] Output was estimated to have been 300 hp (223.7 kW), high enough to flex the block and require a stiffening plate between the bottom of the block and the sump.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] Cunningham used a carbureted version of the engine, and had to reduce the compression ratio to 7.5:1 to accommodate the fuel available to the teams at Le Mans.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] Two C-4R roadsters were built, as well as a single coupe with truncated bodywork designed in collaboration with German aerodynamicist Wunibald Kamm that was designated the C-4RK.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] During practice at the 1952 24 Hours of Le Mans the new transmissions caused problems, and were replaced with 3-speeds.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] In the end the C-4R of Briggs Cunningham and Bill Spear finished fourth overall.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] At the 1953 24 Hours of Le Mans a C-4R roadster finished seventh, and the C-4RK coupe tenth.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] The C-4Rs returned to La Sarthe in 1954 to take third and fifth.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] A C-4R won the 1953 12 Hours of Sebring.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] In 1954, a C-4R driven by Briggs Cunningham and Sherwood Johnston finished sixth in the 12 Hours of Reims.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] A single all-new C-5R was prepared for the 1953 24 Hours of Le Mans.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] The front suspension comprised a solid beam axle sprung by torsion bars.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] This reduced weight by 30 lb (13.6 kg) and allowed the use of 17 in (432 mm) diameter Al-Fin drum brakes mounted inboard of the 16 in (406 mm) wheels.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] At the rear was a live axle on coil springs as on the later C-4Rs.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] The engine remained the Chrysler V8, but power had been increased by 10 hp (7.5 kW).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] A 4-speed transmission from a Fiat truck replaced the earlier 3-speed units.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] When the car arrived at Le Mans for the race the French observers named it "Le Requin Souriant" — the smiling shark.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] At the end of the 24 Hours Walters and Fitch finished first in class and third overall.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] Primary responsibility for the chassis and body design of the C-6R fell to Unger.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] Engines considered for the car included a two-stroke inverted V-12 designed by Mercury Marine's Carl Kiekhaefer, and the Ferrari V-12 from the Italian marque's 375 MM.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] The engine finally chosen was the 179.5 cu in (2,942 cc) four-cylinder Offenhauser from Meyer & Drake.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] After consulting with Leo Goossen, the engine's designer, Cunningham's team managed to get power output up to 270 hp (201.3 kW).
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] The transmission in the C-6R was a four-speed manual by ZF.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] At the 1955 Le Mans the C-6R retired on lap 202.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] Second and third gears had failed, and the engine burned a piston, ending the car's run.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] The car raced at Elkhart Lake a few months later, where the engine failed again.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] The Offy was then replaced by a Jaguar inline-six engine.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] In 2001, former Chrysler chairman Bob Lutz and Briggs Cunningham III (son of company founder Briggs Cunningham II), formed a partnership aiming to revive the company.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] A new car, the Cunningham C7 was revealed at the 2001 Detroit Motor Show.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] Designed by Stewart Reed, the car was a grand tourer styled as a modern interpretation of the Cunningham C-4R.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] The C7 featured a 2+2 seating arrangement and was planned to be equipped with a V12 engine producing 600 horsepower.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] Despite aspirations of producing 500-600 cars a year, priced at around $250,000, the C7 remained a prototype.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] It is claimed that the Cunningham cars were the first to be painted with what are now called racing stripes.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] The International colors for American entries of the time were white bodies with blue frame rails.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] With their enveloping bodywork the Cunningham racers' frame rails were covered, so the obscured blue frame rails were represented by two blue stripes running the length of the cars' bodies.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] These were originally called *Cunningham stripes*.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] Some point to a 1930s Delahaye 145 as an example of prior art.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/b-s-cunningham-company] After winning the Grand Prix du Million prize in 1939, this car had a red and white stripe painted diagonally across the forward part of the blue colored body, completing the French Tricolour.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/big-wheel-tricycle] The original Marx Big Wheel tricycle had rotomolded red, blue, yellow, and black plastic parts.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/big-wheel-tricycle] The seat sits very low to the ground and is adjusted front and back by aligning a pair of large pegs in its base with a desired set of holes molded into the frame.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/big-wheel-tricycle] The large front wheel is approximately 16–18″ in height.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/big-wheel-tricycle] In the 1970s, a handbrake was added in front of the right rear wheel to facilitate intentional spin outs.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/big-wheel-tricycle] Models included the Champion Cycle with a coaster brake in the front wheel, the Mini Sweetheart for toddler girls and the black Cobra Cycle, featuring cobra graphics and a "license plate" that could be personalized.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/big-wheel-tricycle] The design was quickly imitated, under a variety of brand names.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/big-wheel-tricycle] Although "Big Wheel" was a registered trademark, it was frequently used as a generic name for any toy whose design resembled that of Marx.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/big-wheel-tricycle] Following the bankruptcy and liquidation of Marx Toys in the early 1980s, the Big Wheel brand name and molds were sold to Empire Plastics, makers of the Power Cycle brand, which was Marx's biggest competitor.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/big-wheel-tricycle] By the late 1990s, few manufacturers were making these toys.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/big-wheel-tricycle] The Big Wheel brand was reintroduced under new ownership in 2003.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/big-wheel-tricycle] The Big Wheel was inducted into the National Toy Hall of Fame at the Strong in Rochester, New York, in 2009.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/big-wheel-tricycle] In 2021, the Big Wheel brand was acquired by Schylling Inc., a company specializing in classic toys and games.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/big-wheel-tricycle] Annual races are held for Big Wheel-style tricycles in some locations.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/big-wheel-tricycle] One, the "Bring Your Own Big Wheel" race, takes place on Easter Sunday in San Francisco.
[src:chrysler-hemi-engine/big-wheel-tricycle] A Big Wheel race was hosted by the Tulsa Big Wheel Racers LLC as a fundraiser for the Cancer Sucks cancer research center on June 13, 2009.
